# Domain module imports & dependencies

Shared types live in **`packages/domain`** (`migration-domain`). API and worker consume them as a Maven dependency — not as same-source-tree classes.

## Maven dependency (required)

`services/api/pom.xml` and `services/worker/pom.xml` must declare:

```xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>com.migration</groupId>
  <artifactId>migration-domain</artifactId>
  <version>${project.version}</version>
</dependency>
```

When adding a new shared type in domain, rebuild before compiling consumers:

```bash
mvn -pl packages/domain install -DskipTests
```

## Always import domain types in API/worker

In `services/api` or `services/worker`, **always add an explicit import** when using a class from `migration-domain`. Do not assume same-package resolution.

```java
// ❌ BAD — SimulationConfig is in domain, not in services/api
package com.migration.jobs;
// missing import; IDE may show "cannot be resolved"
return SimulationConfig.isSimulation(job.getConfigJson());

// ✅ GOOD
package com.migration.jobs;
import com.migration.simulation.SimulationConfig;
return SimulationConfig.isSimulation(job.getConfigJson());
```

## Avoid split packages

Do **not** add new shared types under `com.migration.jobs` in domain if API already has `com.migration.jobs.*` services (`JobService`, `JobController`, …). Split packages break IDE resolution even when Maven compiles.

Put new shared types in a dedicated domain package:

| Kind | Package example |
|------|-----------------|
| JPA entities / enums | `com.migration.jobs` (existing — already shared) |
| Guards, parsers, config DTOs | `com.migration.simulation`, `com.migration.jobs.config`, etc. |

## Checklist when adding shared Java code

1. Type belongs in `packages/domain`, not duplicated in api/worker.
2. Consumer `pom.xml` has `migration-domain` dependency.
3. Consumer `.java` file has explicit `import com.migration.<pkg>.<Type>;`.
4. Run domain tests + consumer compile/tests.
